\begin_layout Standard
Recall the measurement process in CQT discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Critical-Analysis-CQT"

\end_inset

.
 
\family roman
\size normal
When we measure an observable 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathbf{O}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathbf{O}}\left|i\right\rangle =\lambda_{i}\left|i\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 on a system in a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

, the probability is given by the Born rule of CQT 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\begin{array}{rcccl}
{\cal P}_{\Psi}\left(\ket{i}\right) & = & {\cal P}_{\Psi}\left(\lambda_{i}\right) & = & \frac{\ip{\Psi}{i}\ip{i}{\Psi}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}\ip{i}{i}}\end{array}\ ,\label{prob1.eq-6}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

If the system is in a mixed state represented by a density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\sum_{j}p_{j}\frac{\proj{\Psi_{j}}}{\ip{\Psi_{j}}{\Psi_{j}}}\textrm{ ,}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the Born rule (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob1.eq-6"

\end_inset

) can be extended to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal P}_{\rho}\left(\ket{i}\right)={\cal P}_{\rho}\left(\lambda_{i}\right) & = & \sum_{j}p_{j}{\cal P}_{\Psi_{j}}\left(\ket{i}\right)\textrm{ ,}\label{prob.mixed}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two important properties 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}:\C^{d*}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 have, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\C^{d*}=\left\{ \ket{\Psi}\in\C^{d}\mid\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}\ne0\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the set of non-zero vectors.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under scalar multiplication because a vector still represents
 the same state if we normalize it or multiply it by a global phase.
 Second, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is a probability, and the total probability should be one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, any 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}$
\end_inset

 with these two properties can be identified with a mixed state 
\family roman
\size normal

\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 by Gleason's theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Redhead1987-REDINA,gleason1957,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\size normal
In order to simplify the statement, we consider the probability on the state
 vectors instead of the projectors or closed subspaces as in the Gleason's
 original paper.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

